			],
			"updated": 1774189231091,
			"link": null,
			"locked": true,
			"text": "An important idea for Serialisability is that we should remember write\nskew problem, where T1 read X and Y. updated X. While, T2 read X and Y\nand updated Y.\nSo, the idea is essentially that we maintain a graph of read/writes. We\ndetect if T1 reads the key which T2 laters writes to, then we have a\npossible problem. \n\nThough this method often leads to a few false positives.",
			"rawText": "An important idea for Serialisability is that we should remember write skew problem, where T1 read X and Y. updated X. While, T2 read X and Y and updated Y.\nSo, the idea is essentially that we maintain a graph of read/writes. We detect if T1 reads the key which T2 laters writes to, then we have a possible problem. \n\nThough this method often leads to a few false positives.",
			"fontSize": 20,
			"fontFamily": 5,
			"textAlign": "left",
			"verticalAlign": "top",
			"containerId": null,
			"originalText": "An important idea for Serialisability is that we should remember write skew problem, where T1 read X and Y. updated X. While, T2 read X and Y and updated Y.\nSo, the idea is essentially that we maintain a graph of read/writes. We detect if T1 reads the key which T2 laters writes to, then we have a possible problem. \n\nThough this method often leads to a few false positives.",
			"autoResize": false,
			"lineHeight": 1.25
		},
